10. Maceriam] This is the only place in Terence or Plautus where this word occurs. ‘ Maceria’ properly means ⁸ a boundary wall' enclosing a piece of ground. The term was confined to what we call a wall, in distinction from a fence, made of stones,

,bricks, or flints. Caesar (Bell. Gall. vii. 69) uses it apparently of a wall made in haste of loose stones. See Long's note. It is probably connected with ‘ macellum,' which is derived, according to Festus, from μάκελον or μάκελλον. See Forcellini (Ma- cellum .
